        <div class="c-article-body">
            <section aria-labelledby="Abs1" data-title="Abstract" lang="en"><div class="c-article-section" id="Abs1-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Abs1">Abstract</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Abs1-content"><p>Clonal haematopoiesis arises when a haematopoietic stem cell (HSC) acquires a mutation that confers a competitive advantage over wild-type HSCs, resulting in its clonal expansion. Individuals with clonal haematopoiesis are at increased risk of developing haematologic neoplasms and other age-related inflammatory illnesses<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Jaiswal, S. et al. Clonal hematopoiesis and risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. N. Engl. J. Med. 377, 111–121 (2017)." href="#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d508818e856">1</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Jaiswal, S. et al. Age-related clonal hematopoiesis associated with adverse outcomes. N. Engl. J. Med. 371, 2488–2498 (2014)." href="#ref-CR2" id="ref-link-section-d508818e856_1">2</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Genovese, G. et al. Clonal hematopoiesis and blood-cancer risk inferred from blood DNA sequence. N. Engl. J. Med. 371, 2477–2487 (2014)." href="#ref-CR3" id="ref-link-section-d508818e856_2">3</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 4" title="Weeks, L. D. &amp; Ebert, B. L. Causes and consequences of clonal hematopoiesis. Blood 142, 2235–2246 (2023)." href="/articles/s41586-025-08871-w#ref-CR4" id="ref-link-section-d508818e859">4</a></sup>. Suppressing the expansion of mutant HSCs may prevent these outcomes; however, such interventions have not yet been identified. The most common clonal haematopoiesis driver mutations are in the <i>DNMT3A</i> gene, with arginine 882 (R882) being a mutation hotspot<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Jaiswal, S. et al. Clonal hematopoiesis and risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. N. Engl. J. Med. 377, 111–121 (2017)." href="#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d508818e866">1</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Jaiswal, S. et al. Age-related clonal hematopoiesis associated with adverse outcomes. N. Engl. J. Med. 371, 2488–2498 (2014)." href="#ref-CR2" id="ref-link-section-d508818e866_1">2</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 3" title="Genovese, G. et al. Clonal hematopoiesis and blood-cancer risk inferred from blood DNA sequence. N. Engl. J. Med. 371, 2477–2487 (2014)." href="/articles/s41586-025-08871-w#ref-CR3" id="ref-link-section-d508818e869">3</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Bick, A. G. et al. Inherited causes of clonal haematopoiesis in 97,691 whole genomes. Nature 586, 763–768 (2020)." href="#ref-CR5" id="ref-link-section-d508818e872">5</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Buscarlet, M. et al. DNMT3A and TET2 dominate clonal hematopoiesis and demonstrate benign phenotypes and different genetic predispositions. Blood 130, 753–762 (2017)." href="#ref-CR6" id="ref-link-section-d508818e872_1">6</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 7" title="Ley, T. J. et al. DNMT3A mutations in acute myeloid leukemia. N. Engl. J. Med. 363, 2424–2433 (2010)." href="/articles/s41586-025-08871-w#ref-CR7" id="ref-link-section-d508818e875">7</a></sup>. Here we show that mouse haematopoietic stem and progenitor cells (HSPCs) carrying the <i>Dnmt3a</i><sup>R878H/+</sup> mutation, equivalent to human <i>DNMT3A</i><sup>R882H/+</sup>, have increased mitochondrial respiration compared with wild-type cells and are dependent on this metabolic reprogramming for their competitive advantage. Treatment with metformin, an anti-diabetic drug that inhibits mitochondrial respiration<sup><a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 8" title="Bridges, H. R. et al. Structural basis of mammalian respiratory complex I inhibition by medicinal biguanides. Science 379, 351–357 (2023)." href="/articles/s41586-025-08871-w#ref-CR8" id="ref-link-section-d508818e888">8</a></sup>, reduced the competitive advantage of <i>Dnmt3a</i><sup>R878H/+</sup> HSCs. Through a multi-omics approach, we found that metformin acts by enhancing methylation potential in <i>Dnmt3a</i><sup>R878H/+</sup> HSPCs and reversing the aberrant DNA CpG methylation and histone H3 K27 trimethylation profiles in these cells. Metformin also reduced the competitive advantage of human <i>DNMT3A</i><sup>R882H</sup> HSPCs generated by prime editing. Our findings provide preclinical rationale for investigating metformin as a preventive intervention against <i>DNMT3A</i> R882 mutation-driven clonal haematopoiesis in humans.</p></div></div></section>

            
                
